In 1268 the University came into serious conflict with the jews, an important colony of whom had settled in Oxford soon after the Conquest. They had

. built houses in St.A1date's, and when Henry ll freed

all Jews from the obligation of bringing their dead to London for burial‚ they purchased a cemetery where Magdalen College now stands. Their extortionate rate of usury‚ their attempts to induce young scholars to join their religion, their improper treatment of ecclesiastical plate pledged to them, and mockery of Christian festivals soon brought them into disfavour. Asearly as 1180 a Jew called ‘ Deus-eum·crescat’ was , accustomed to mock at the miracles performed at the shrine of St. Fridcswyde. ‘Halting and then walking firmly on his feet, showing his hands clenched as if with palsy and then flinging open his fingers he claimed gifts and oblations from the crowd who flocked to St. Fridcswyde's, on the ground that such recoveries of limb and strength were quite as real as any Fridcswyde had wrought.' In 1244 certain scholars broke open the houses in the Jewry and robbed them of much money.
